<paper id="1984361668"><title>Graph partitioning using single commodity flows</title><year>2009</year><authors><author org="IBM Thomas J. Watson Research Center, Hawthorne, New York" id="2330085442">Rohit Khandekar</author><author org="University of California Berkeley, CA#TAB#" id="2108675760">Satish Rao</author><author org="University of California Berkeley, CA#TAB#" id="391723092">Umesh Vazirani</author></authors><n_citation>44</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>1588155622</reference><reference>1966461475</reference><reference>1974785036</reference><reference>1977545325</reference><reference>1993111701</reference><reference>1995547833</reference><reference>2018804864</reference><reference>2020632401</reference><reference>2024778356</reference><reference>2045107949</reference><reference>2051540665</reference><reference>2070232376</reference><reference>2078013954</reference><reference>2098651744</reference><reference>2099463627</reference><reference>2107881198</reference><reference>2117595194</reference><reference>2120970098</reference><reference>2125062050</reference><reference>2150148016</reference><reference>2161455936</reference><reference>2165956524</reference><reference>2169124940</reference><reference>2176446742</reference></references><venue id="118992489" type="J">Journal of the ACM</venue><doi>10.1145/1538902.1538903</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.51688">Cut</keyword><keyword weight="0.52385">Graph theory</keyword><keyword weight="0.45698">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.53423">Approximation algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Graph</keyword><keyword weight="0.45841">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.50973">Vertex (geometry)</keyword><keyword weight="0.43398">Spectral method</keyword><keyword weight="0.53007">Graph partition</keyword><keyword weight="0.40433">Mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.44743">Computation</keyword></keywords><publisher>ACM</publisher><abstract>We show that the sparsest cut in graphs with n vertices and m edges can be approximated within O(log2 n) factor in O(m + n3/2) time using polylogarithmic single commodity max-flow computations. Previous algorithms are based on multicommodity flows that take time O(m + n2). Our algorithm iteratively employs max-flow computations to embed an expander flow, thus providing a certificate of expansion. Our technique can also be extended to yield an O(log2 n)-(pseudo-) approximation algorithm for the edge-separator problem with a similar running time.</abstract></paper>